When sed is built with GCC, there is a significant performance regression
compared to Studio, related to strncmp (used inside the STREQ_LEN macro)
not being inlined.

The newly added streq_len is correctly inlined, and the resulting binary
is as fast as the Studio one.

This can be reported to the gcc upstream.

--- sed-4.10/sed/execute.c
+++ sed-4.10/sed/execute.c
@@ -1186,6 +1186,19 @@ do_subst (struct subst *sub)
     output_line (line.active, line.length, line.chomped, sub->outf);
 }
 
+static inline bool
+streq_len (const char *s1, const char *s2, size_t n)
+{
+  while (n-- != 0)
+    {
+      if (*s1 != *s2++)
+        return false;
+      if (*s1++ == '\0')
+        return true;
+    }
+  return true;
+}
+
 /* Translate the global input LINE via TRANS.
    This function handles the multi-byte case.  */
 static void
@@ -1206,7 +1219,7 @@ translate_mb (char *const *trans)
       /* 'i' indicate i-th translate pair.  */
       for (i = 0; trans[2*i] != NULL; i++)
         {
-          if (STREQ_LEN (line.active + idx, trans[2*i], mbclen))
+          if (streq_len (line.active + idx, trans[2*i], mbclen))
             {
               bool move_remain_buffer = false;
               const char *tr = trans[2*i+1];
